			<h1>Stiefel Game</h1>
			<h2>It’s Your Turn … The Stiefel Game</h2>
			<h4>Time to roll up those sleeves and get serious – Passing the Stiefel is not for the faint of heart, nor is it faint of liver, fainting as the Stiefel is passed to you is definitely not permissible in the game, but let’s find out more…Prost!! Let’s Get Started…<h4>

			<h2>1. Stiefel Game!!?? How is it Played?</h2>
			<h4>A group of people 3 or more stand in a circle with a full Stiefel, one person begins the game by taking one drink from the Stiefel, after which, this person passes the Stiefel to the person on their right. The Stiefel continues to be passed around in this fashion until it is finished, which determines the loser. One would think that when playing the Stiefel game, all participants are winners, but alas every contest requires a loser. In this case, the loser is the person to the left of the individual who finished the Boot. Simply put, this person did not drink enough of the Boot (for whatever reason) and thus passed (up) their opportunity to finish the Stiefel. The loser then must either pay for the next Boot, in Germany can amount to 30 Euros or nearly 50 dollars, or has to fill up the next Boot, probably more likely. The rounds continue until:</h4>
			<h4>A) All the beer is finished.</h4>
			<h4>B) There is no one left standing.</h4>
			<h4>C) The Stiefel is broken.</h4>
			<h4>D) All of the above, which if all occurred in the same round would be the ‘Perfect Storm’ Anyway you all get the idea, but wait … before you can start, please brush up on the rules and regulations.</h4>
			
			<h2>2. What is the Objective?</h2>
			<h4>Interesting question, actually the objective can vary from person to person, especially when the Stiefel is in one’s hand. But the objective of the game is NOT to be the standing to the left of the person who finishes the Stiefel.</h4>

			<h2>3. How many players can ‘pass the stiefel’?</h2>
			<h4>The great part of the Stiefel Game is that all you need to start pass the Stiefel is three people. A game with two people isn’t much of a game, and one person is just plain sad or boring, you pick. But, once there are three people, the game can begin, and it can expand to include any number of people. 6, 8, even 12 people can play, just guarantee that there is enough beer to feed all those mouths.</h4>

			<h2>4. I can’t just take a drink from the Stiefel?</h2>
			<h4>Unfortunately, there are a few very important rules for drinking from the Stiefel when it is your turn, which could dictate the outcome of the Stiefel round.</h4>
			<h4>To begin your turn, before picking up the Stiefel, you must tap the surface on which the Stiefel is placed with your elbow (drinking arm preferred) then slap (gently) the Stiefel with the back of your drinking hand. This action announces to the group that your turn is in effect. If anyone else other than you touches the Stiefel after you have completed this process, it is grounds for forfeit and the guilty party has lost the round. There is no time limit for your turn; however, to maintain the atmosphere of the game, it is best to end your turn quickly.</h4>
			<h4>After you complete the opening move, you must choose how to pick up the Stiefel. The Stiefel CANNOT be rotated once it leaves the surface on which it was placed. Rotation after it is lifted from the surface is grounds for forfeit. There are two positions you can hold the Stiefel prior to lifting it off the the surface, and this is very important so heed:
			You can choose to drink from the Stiefel with TOE of the Stiefel facing away from you (the drinker) This announces to the group that you will not finish the contents in the Stiefel. The TOE of the Stiefel will point Up when lifted from the surface.</h4>
			<h4>Or, you can choose to drink from the Stiefel with the TOE of the Stiefel facing toward you (the drinker). This announces to the group that you will finish the Stiefel. The TOE of the Stiefel will point DOWN when lifted from the surface. It is only in this position, with the TOE facing down or towards the drinker, that one can finish the Stiefel. Remember there are two options prior to lifting the Stiefel, but you can take only ONE drink from the Stiefel during your turn, so put on your game face and Good Luck!</h4>

			<h2>5. What happens after I can’t drink any more?</h2>
			<h4>Well that all depends which way the TOE of the Stiefel was pointed when you picked up the Stiefel. If you chose the prudent course, Numeral I, and drank with the TOE facing up, after reaching your fill, place the Stiefel back on the surface from which the Stiefel was lifted. Repeat Step 4.1 to end your turn. Pass the Stiefel to the person on your right, and hope that you left too much beer for them to finish.</h4>
			<h4>If you chose to impress everyone at the party and drank from the Stiefel with the TOE facing down, the Stiefel should be dry when you set it back down again. When you set it down, place the Stiefel on its side and watch intensely to watch if any beer drips out of the Stiefel. If no beer escapes the Stiefel, you have successfully finished the Stiefel and now can place the empty Stiefel in the hands of the person to your left to refill and savor your triumph. But, if beer happens to escape from the Stiefel, you will be held responsible for the blunder and considered the loser of the round. You will have refill the Stiefel and probably your pride.</h4>

			<h2>6. Regulations that must not be dismissed.</h2>
			<h4>There are a few regulations and traditions that should be followed to heighten the enjoyment of the game.</h4>
			<h4>Penalties. Probably the most fun of the game. These are not the same as forfeit. Forfeits end the round; Penalties are administered during the round and carry over into the subsequent rounds. The principle Game Foul that warrants a penalty is spillage from the Stiefel while one is drinking from the Stiefel, using resulting in a wet face, wet shirt or both. This is where the fun comes in, prior to the start of the game or round, the group should agree upon a certain penalty for this mistake. Some sample suggestions are: for males: must wear a bra for the rest of the round or game; for males/females can only drink beer from a children’s bottle; for males/females for the penalized they must take a shot (of any beverage) before every subsequent turn of theirs; etc. You get the idea, the possibilities are limitless.</h4>
			<h4>The main reason for spillage of the Stiefel is what has been appropriately coined ‘Glub Glub.’ For those who have seen Beerfest, you should have guessed what this is, if you haven’t it won’t be long until you experience the ‘Glub Glub.’</h4>
			<h4>Now that you the have rules and regulations, all you need is a Stiefel. Visit the Stiefel Store to get your hands on a Stiefel. After you have played a few rounds of the Stiefel Game, please send in any pictures, modifications to the game rules and penalties, and new names for the ‘Glub Glub.’ As the Stiefel has multiple histories, it can also have multiple versions of the game. Prost !!</h4>
